{"/service/ndnp/az/batch_az_fireant_ver01/data/sn84021912/00211104351/1907112001/0298.xml":{"full_text":"Arizona Sentinel.\nWEDNESDAY, NOV. 20, 1907.\nAttorney General Bonepafcte\nis going to ask the courts to de\nfine what whiskey is. Probably\nthey will differ as much in then\ndefinitions as they do as to what\nconstitutes a drunk.\nA modern dude with narrow\nstriped clothes, saddle colored\nshoes, aloud necktie, hair parted\nover his nose, and smoking a\ncigarette, addressed his best girl\nthus: \"If you was me and I was\nyou, what would you do?'' She\nhesitatingly said with a smile: \"I\nwould take off that hideous tie,\nput that cigarette in the stove,\npart my hair on one side, then\npray-to God for brains.\"\nThat our American rorests abound In\nplants which possess the most valuable\nmedicinal virtues is abundantly attested\nby scores of the most eminent medical\nwriters and teachers. Even the untu\ntored Indians had discovered the useful\nness of many native plants before the\nadvent of the white race. This informa\ntion, imparted freely to the whites, led\nthe latter to continue investigations until\nto-day wo Jiavc a rich assortment of most\nvaluable American medicinal roots.\nDr. Pierce believes that our American for\nests aUfepd In most valuable medicinal roct3\nfoa the cmtijf most obstinate and fatal dis\neases, if wcwtid properly Investigate them;\nand laoHBrBiAtNtfi of this conviction, he\npolrrfcrwith prilTiSA the almost, jnfirrplnn\nFine Stock\nPossibly no town in our state\nwith a population not greater\nthan is claimed here, can boast\nof as many good horses as are\nowned by our local horsemen.\nGreat as has been the future pre\ndiceted for the automobile, man\nhas manifested no in-eat desire\nto forsake his old friend, the horse\nand today fine roadsters are in\ngreater demand than ever before.\nNot only are good roadsters\neagerly sought, but those stand\nard bred and of acknowledge\nspeed are also coming in for their\nshare of the honors.\ncover.v.\" reMch h-$ prpvpp Ucelf to tv the\nmost pp'r'\"nt g'ornnr-h tonic, liver Innrcr\natcr. hnart tonlo anfl regulator, and bipod\ncleanser known to m.cdicr.l science. Dyspep\nsia, or indigestion, torpid MfcrTttmctlonal\nand even valvular and other affections of\nthe heart yield to its curative action. The\nreason u7iy It cures these and many other\naffections. Is clearly shown in a little book\nof extracts from the standard medical works\nvrhlch is mailed free to any address by Dr. R.\nV. Pierce, of Buffalo. N. Y., to all sending\nrequest for the same.\nO\nKot less marvelous. In the unparalleled\neuros- it is constantly making of woman's\nmany peculiar affections, weaknesses and\ndlstrCSshie derailments. 13 Dr. Pierce's\nFaTOritcNPrescripUoias Is amply attested\nby thousands ofnKAUjiledJestlmonlals con\ntributed byVcfcrfeful patltMws who have been\ncurci byjt oLcatnrrhal rvolvlc qrf.ms, painii.i\npeiiocis,. Irregularities, nrolanus jnd'o:ne'r\ndisnlacpmcnis. cauyetr'by weakiiPSx ulcer-C-tlonof\nw? cms naTindrpdaTfcctlpns often\nafter\"many other advertised medicines, and\nphysicians had failed.\n-0 ix O\nBoth the above mentioned medicines are\nwholly made up from the glyceric extracts of\nnative, medicinal roots. The processes em\nployed In their manufacture were original\nvrtth Dr. Pierce, and they arc carried cn by\nskilled chemists and pharmacists with the\naid of apparatus and appliances specially\ndesigned and built for this purpose. Lotn\nmedicines are entirely free from alcohol ana\nall other harmful, habit-forming drugs. A\nfull list of their ingredients is printed on\noslcK hattle-wranaer.\nThere is perhaps nothing\nthat interfere more with effective\nschool work than parties given\nduring school week. If the time\nactually spent at the party alone\nbe considered, the ill-eflects on\nschool work would possibly not\nbe so marked. But experience\nhas taught all of us that the mind\ncannot be centered on school\nwork, either while anticipating\na jovial time or while the im\npressions 01 a mgnc or amuse\nment are fresh in our memories\nOhio Federation of Labor\nFor Woman Suifrage\nAt its regular annual meeting\nheld in Columbus, the Ohio Fed\neration of Labor adopted a reso\nhition. calling upon the State\nLegislature to adopt a resolution,\nat the coming sessiou, \"request\ning the Congress of the United\noiaies to suomic to tne various\nStates Legislatures for ratifica\ntion an amendment to the United\nStates Constitution prohibitin\ndisfranchisemant on account of\nsex.\" The secretary was in\nstructed to send copies of this\nresolution to the Governor of the\nState, to the Clerk of the House\nand the Clerk of the Senate.\nAmong other State Federa\ntions of Labor which have offici\nally declared for woman suffrage\nare, Connecticut, Colorado, Cali\nfornia, Iowa, Indiana, Massachu\nsetts, Minnesota, Michigan,\nMaine, New Hampshire, Ohio,\nUregon, Oaklahoma and \"West\nVirginia.\nFattening Poultry\nFarmers lose thousands of dol\nlars every year by sending to\nmarket unf attened poultry. Pro\nfessional fatteners sometimes\ndouble the weight of a bird in\nthree weeks. It is easy to add a\npound or more to the weight of\na thin bird. Not only the added\nweight is an advantage, but the\nwell fattend bird sells for a high\ner price per pound. A double\ngain. Corn is the great fatten\ning grain, but makes yellow flesh\nOats makes white flesh. Most\nAmerican markets demand yel\nlow flesh and skin, though the\ndemand is growing for white\nfleshed fowls. The fowls should\nbe confined' rather 'closely and\nfed all they will eat clean. A\nmixture of equal parts of ground\ncorn, oats and bran) with the ad\ndition of charcoal, wet up with\nmilk, but not so as to be sloppy,\nis a good fattener. Feed this\ntwice daily and corn once, with\nplenty of water and some green\nstuff, and it will found the most\nprofitable way to market the\ncorn.\nA Guaranteed Cure tor Piles.\nItehipg, Blind, Bleeding, Protruding\nPiles. Druggists :itp authorized to re\nfund money ifPAZO OTNTMENT fails\ntP cure in G to 14 days. 50c.\nTHE YUMA EXHIBIT\nWhat Can Be Grown on the Rich\nLands of the Colorado Delta\nPhoenix Republican The\nYuma count7 exhibit in the ag\nricultural department over which\nMr. Wilson presides, is one de\nserving of special mention. W.\nE. Lynch is the Yuma county\ncommissioner to whose efforts\nthis exhibit is largely due and\nwho is in charge of it here. It\ncannot all be told here but this\nis an index.\nCotton raising is destined to\nbe a Yuma county industry and\nthe best cotton in the world at\nthat, the Egyptian cotton which\ndemands the highest pri6e in the\nmarket. The experiment station\nat Yuma sends a cotton plant of\nthis variety eight feet high,\nheavily laden with the \"fruit.'\nFrom the same farm come plant\nalso of Rogers Big Boll, and\nColumbia varities. It is claimed\nthat the Rodgers produces three\nbales to the acre\nThere is a display of fine\nbrooms made by W. W. Hanna;\ndates grown, in Yuma: a grape\nvine from George Ricks' ranch\nforty feet long; six water melons\nweighing 290 pounds grown by\nNewt Parks; and a sample of al\nfalfa seed which returned 541\npounds tt) the acre last year and\non tne strengtn or wnicn tnere\nwere more orders this year than\ncould be filled. There is a table\nbeet weighing 22 pounds, some\nA 1 paper shell pecan nuts from\nthe ranch of General Ingalls, a\nfine lot of pearstfrom the Ricks\nranch; oranges, lemons and\ngrape fruit from Yuma heights,\nand the largest known thin rind\nlemon. These lemons are almost\nas large as grape fruit and the\nrind is almost as thin as paper\nmere are also some nne grapes\nand some enormous sweet pota\ntoes; Chili green and ripe, string\nbeans eight inches long; pickled\nolives of fine quality aud partic\nular attention is called to some\nsecond crop Muscat and Flaming\nTokay grapes. There is a real\nnovelty limb from a Japanese\npersimmon tree, heavily laden\nwith \"simmons,\" bigger than a\nhen's egg. There isan exhibit\nof sorghum 18 feet high that has\nnot yet headed out and some\nhoney, with some more honey\nboth comb and strained, in the\napiary department.\nYuma also has exhibits in the\nWoman's department and at other\nplaces on the grounds.\nTHANKSGIVING DAY\nA Proclamation by the Governor.'\n$50,000,000 in Panama\nBonds and 1100,000,000\nin Certificates to be issued\nWashington, D. C, Nov 18\nSecretary of the treasury Cortel\nyou has issued an order for the\nissuance of of 850,000,000 in Pan\nama bonds and 100,000,000 in 3\nper cent certificates of indebted\nness. The proceeds of the bond\nsale will be deposited in the banks\npurchasing the oonds, thus put\nting the entire cash influx of the\nsale into circulation. This action\nis expected to give permanent\nand immediate relief to the finan\ncial situation.\nTo the People of Arizona:\nOf all our national holidays,\nthat one which is the most pe\nculiarly American is near at\nhand. It seems eminently right\nthat Thanksgiving Day should be\none of our greatest holidays, for\nit is a national belief that\nour beloved and favored\ncountry is in the especial keeping\nof Divine Providence.\nMoreover, the day has become\nhallowed, in all places where\nAmericans are to be found, by\nour own custom of family re\nunions for its celebration.\" It is\nthus a holiday of happy thanks\ngiving, a holiday of joyous meet\nings, and a holiday in which\nmemories of tjae past have a sac\nred part.\nAnd because most of us have\nleft homes elsewhere in order to\nestablish homes in Arizona, there\nis perhaps, no other section of\nthe Union in which the day is\nmore generally welcomed or its\nsignificance more appreciated.\nThe president of the United\nStates has designated Thursday,\nthe twenty-eighth day of this\nmonth as Thanksgiving Day for\nthis year.\nNow therefore, I Joseph H.\nKibbey, Governor of Arizona, do\nhereby designate THURSDAY,\nNOVEMBER 28, 1907, as\nTHANKSGIVING DAY in this\nTerritory, and I recommend to\nthe people that they observe the\nday in a proper spirit and man\nner, in accordance with their own\nsense of obligation and of whole\nsome pleasure.\nIn Witness Whereof, I have\nhereunto set my hand and caused\nthe Great Seal of the Territory\nto be affixed. Done at the City\nof Phoenix, the. Capital, this\neleventh day of November, nine\nteen hundred and seven.\n(Seal) JOSEPH H. KIBBEY.\nBy the Governor:\nW. F. NICHOLS,\nSecretary of the Territory\n(I. T.) of Arizona.\nj J. ML MOLINA 1\nf Qeeeral .Merchandise j\nMain Street, Between Second and Third.\nTELEPHONE 31\nI Port Yuma Store\nTelephone 2.\nasratraifcsn gar\nLOOK OVER YOUR HARNESS\nCAREFULLY.\nIf it isn't all you want it to be come\nin and see our harness styles, strength,\nworkmanship and\" values. There's no\ncompulsion even insistence about\nbuying. If you're pleased 'with mate\nrial and prices of course you'll find it\nto your interest to buy without our\nurging or even asking you. Come in.\nJOHNSON BOWLES\nPHONE 62\nSuch Is Life.\nnr il l'\nman mat is oorn or nis par\nents is of few days and full of\nmicrobes. He goeth to school\nvchen a youngster and gets the\nseat of his pants paddled for\nsomething he didn't do until he\nis sick at heart. He groxeth up\nlike a weed in a back yard, and\nsoon reaches the age when he is\ncomposed largely of feet, freckles\nand an appetite for pie. About\nthe time he gets too long for\nshort trousers and not Ion\nenough for long ones he goeth\naway to college, learneth how to\nmonkey with a three dollar man\ndolin and play whiskey poker\nHe cometh home a bigger fool\nthan ever and marrieth a sweet\nyoung thing whose pa is suppos\ned to be wealthy, but whom he\nsubsequently ascertaineth, could\nn't buy the prize rooster at\ncounty fair. He worrieth along\nfrom year to year, gradually ac\nquiring offsprings, until his\nhouse resembles a Sunday school\nclass just before Christmas. He\nf retteth through the day and lieth\nawake nights trying go figure out\nhow to keep himself and his de\npendent population out- of the\npoor house. Efforts are reward\noy naving nis aaugoters run\naway and get married and bring\nhim home a nice son-in-law every\nfew days to feast at his bo.;r(.\nHis sons grow up and call him\ngovernor and set him back a rive\nspot every day or two. About\nthe time he has acquired enough\nlucre to make it worth while for\nhis heirs to quarrel over he con\ntracts a cold and is hurried away\nbefore he has time to have a talk\nwith his family. His sons blow\nin his estate on bad whiskey and\nplug hats, and his wife puts the\nnnisning toucnes to nis career\nby marrying the hired man.\nPension Attorneys Disbarred.\nOld soldiers all over the count\nry can feel a real interest in the\naction of the Interior Department\nin disbarring one firm of pension\nattorneys from practice and in-\nstitu ting proceedings agai nst sev\neral others. The trouble was\nspeculation on the part of the\nnsion sharks in land bounty\nscript. This script is issued to\nall soldiers and their widows and\nheirs who participated in any\nAmerican war back of 1855.\nThere are a suprising number of\nthese decendents in the country\nwho have never applied for their\nland bounty. The pension firms\nin question made a practice of\nlooking up these old claims and\nnotifying the beneficiaries so that\nthe claims could be pushed\nthrough, the attorneys, of course\ngetting the regular fee for the\nwork. But then it was the habit\nof many of the attorneys to buy\nthe land script from the success\nful claimant at an average 1.25\nper acre, the claims were for 160\nacres, and sell the script to some\noutsider, often as high as from\nfive to ten dollars per acre.\nMost of the old land claimants\ndid not even know they were be\ning robbed, for that was what it\namounted to. But Secretary\nGarfield took the matter up and\nnow one firm has been disbarred\nfrom practice and others are\ntrembling. Of course, it is a\ngood thing to protect the pen\nsioners from graft, but the beauty\nof the incident from a public\nviewpoint is that it indicates the\nInterior Department is going to\nbe run on a more honest and bus\niness like basis than formerly.\nSome Sound Advise\nDun's weekly review of condi\ntions in Southern California gives\nsome wholesome advise, when it\nsays:\nDo not talk distrust. Fear par\nalizes mental and muscular eng\nergy. Confidence is the basis of\nbusiness. Without confidence\nnot a grain of wheat would be\nsown, not a tree planted nor an\nindustrial wheel turned. Do not\nsacrifice. Investments on a bus\niness basis are all right. If you\nhave withdrawn money from\ncirculation, it is a good time to\nreinvest in interest paying se\ncurities. Or, put it where it can\nbe used in carrying on thet)usi\nness of this section. It is a buy\ners marlret. Thes amount of\nmoney available for reserve with\nyour banker has an influence on\nthe volume of credits. Remem\nber the financial condition of the\nindividual depends on the finan\ncial condition of the community\nin which he lives. Sel\nfish hoarding of money in times\nlike these is a short-sighted fool\nish policy, tending to check our\nforward movement by inviting\nbusiness st ignation. Go about\nyour business in the normal way.\nBring yo; r .un.y out of the\ndark. Do it u.s a matter of in\ntelligence if better motives do\nnot prompt. The hoarders of the\neast, if they did not cause the\nsituation there, supplied its most\ndangerous element.\nThe sound sense of these sug\ngestions, coming from any source\nwould be obvious, But when\nthey are made by one of the\ngreat commercial agencies, of\nknown conservatism and thor\nough knowledge of the situation,\nthey should have the utmost\nweight with every thinking per\nson.\nAll cities are provincal, but\nNew York is the most provincial\nof American cities. Its people\ncannot see beyond the sky lines\nof its tall buildings. They did\nnot Know, untni tne trutn was\nforced upon them, that their wa\ntered stock an other forms of\nfictitious wealth was a mockery\nin which the country at large had\nlittle interest.\nThe people are begining to yell\nat the banks, like the fans on the\ndiamond, \"Play ball\" and it looks\nnow as though the banks were\nheeding the admonition.\nAnd so the pendulum swings\nagain twoard prosperity, and\nwhile times may pinch a little\nhere and there, an improvement\nhas set in, and it ought not be\nmany days before the people for\nget events of the last few days in\na general return of prosperity.\nMineral Standard.\nFor you could not find a better\nor ir.oie useful article than s.\nWe have a complete line.\nPriest from SI SO fr R10.fM.\nLet us remind you that right\nPll no w s me; to Pfc6 onc; ou\n\"wc guarantee wb.\n\"See Siiorey About It'\nNew Gandolfo Block\nOffice Yuma Daily Examiner\nur\nwill cdl\ne\nThe people of Yuma have\naccess to an acknowledg\ned standard, world-wide\nadvertised Shoe, ta the\nprice that it is sold at\nwhere it is Made.\nWo L. Douglas\n$3eS0 Shoe\nin all styles and ail leath\ners; high cutanU low cut;\nall sizes and all widths,\n'and the one price of\n$3.50 per pair\nCan be found at\nE. F. SANGUINETTI'S\nMODERN DEPARTMENT STORE.\nSpecial Attention to nail Orders.\ni\nED. AND BEN HODGES,\nPACIF\nBEST HOTEL IN YUHA\nRemodeled and Refurnished by the Mew Management.\nDininp Room the Best in Yuma AiryVhite Help.\nGOOD SAMPLE ROOMS IN CONNECTION\nProprietors\nJOHNSON fr BOWLES\n(Incorporated)\nDEALERS IN\nHARNESS\nCROCKERY, GLASSWARE\nAIM\nNext Door to IPostoffice\nREAL ESTATE\nLOANS\nINSURANCE\nGENERAL\nAGENTS\nfntablished in I899\nIncorporated I906\nTitle-Abstract Co.\nAbstracts of Title\nto all Lands, Town\nLots, Mines and\nCanals in Yuma County.\nYUMA, ARIZONA I\nJOHNSON BOWLES,\nUNDERTAKERS AND EMBALMERS\nF. W. MURPHY, Director. Open Nights.\nPendulum Swings Backward\nHere is for better times! The\npendulum has begun to swing\ntwoard prosperity again.\nThe action of Secretary Cortel-\nyou in transferring arold from the\nNew York to interior banks has\nhad a good effect In York as\nwell as olsewhct Cor Hiey are;\nheeding the demand that they re- j\nturn to rationul methods. I\nWe want\nYour trade\nand we're going to fret it if the best\nmeats, the best strvics und lowest\nprices in town will interest you. This\nis a market where your dollar buys ii\ngood one hundred cents' worth and Vou\nstill have a little change coming.\nuy your\ne Res:\nIt will mean a saving to you of cash,\ntrouble and waiting for goods you want\nin a hurry; we deliver promptly. It,\nwill pay you to study our prices; the\nbest way to study them is to come in\nand compare our prices with what you\nwill pay at the other butcher shops.\nF. and E. Hodges\ni ilea! Market\nPhone. 23\nNIGHT PHOFE\n96\nCor. ftiain and Third Sts.\nLady Assistant'\nDAY PHONE\n62\nHOME PHONE 404\nNEWLY FITTED, FURNISHED, RENOVATED\nROOMS BY DAY, WEEK\nOR MONTH, 50c PER DAY\nAND UP.\nMRS. A. L, ROBERTS. Manager\nWest Main Stpeet\nnear the mission\nlonsi Looging\nVENTURA. GAL.\ns\nto Sat.\nInternational\nRestaurant\nFirst and ftSain\n1U.-U ouoss is the .s&st a\n.Alexander-- Co, the up-to-date gro-1\ncers.\nCOFFEE\nThe world is full ofej\nanonymous coffee \"JayaC\nand Mocha.\"\nWho returns your\nmoney if you don't like\n'em?\nYour grocer returns your money if you doai j\nlike Schilling's Best: we pay him.- j.","height":"28992","width":"20754"}}
